ce:section.ce:para:
The chemical compositions of R-CDs were investigated by photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS). There are three typical peaks at 533 eV (O 1s), 399 eV (N 1s) and 285 eV (C 1s) in the XPS, suggesting that our prepared R-CDs are consisted of O, N and C elements (Fig. 1d). The atomic percentages of C, N and O are 80.23 %, 12.84 %, and 6.93 %, respectively. We further analyzed the high-resolution XPS of these elements. From the Fig. S1a, it can be seen that three different states of carbon: CO (288.0 eV), CN (284.6 eV) and CC
                        /C=C (283.8 eV) were contained in this R-CDs. The high-resolution XPS spectrum of N 1s (Fig. S1b) also contains three different peaks at 398.2, 399.0 and 399.9 eV, which represent pyridinic N, amino N and pyrrolic N, respectively. It indicates that the R-CDs contain a lot of nitrogen-containing ring structures. From O element, only one peak is found at 531.4 eV, attributing to the CO bond (Fig. S1c). From the results of XPS and FTIR, we can see that there are a large number of -NH2, pyridine and other hydrophilic groups (CO, CN, CC
                        ) on the surface of the R-CDs, which are in favor of lysosomes targeting [29]. In addition, delocalized positive cation lipophilic cationic moieties are prerequisite for mitochondria targeting [30]. The zeta potential value of R-CDs is 24.4 mV (Fig. S2), revealing that the surface of is positive charge. The delocalized structures and positive charge make the R-CDs suitable for targeting mitochondria [31].
